{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/windows-file-structure/","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Blogs By Jai-D"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"994b9113-b863-543d-8ef5-503f5393b292","excerpt":"If like the 76.65% per of people you also use windows then you must have encountered an error like this while trying to rename your file/folder to be more…","html":"<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 700px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blogs/static/5eacea63ee1d6be8b737dd7fb9fce7b6/21b4d/OSper.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 55.99999999999999%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Desktop OS market Share\"\n        title=\"Desktop OS market Share\"\n        src=\"/blogs/static/5eacea63ee1d6be8b737dd7fb9fce7b6/8c557/OSper.png\"\n        srcset=\"/blogs/static/5eacea63ee1d6be8b737dd7fb9fce7b6/4edbd/OSper.png 175w,\n/blogs/static/5eacea63ee1d6be8b737dd7fb9fce7b6/13ae7/OSper.png 350w,\n/blogs/static/5eacea63ee1d6be8b737dd7fb9fce7b6/8c557/OSper.png 700w,\n/blogs/static/5eacea63ee1d6be8b737dd7fb9fce7b6/e996b/OSper.png 1050w,\n/blogs/static/5eacea63ee1d6be8b737dd7fb9fce7b6/21b4d/OSper.png 1280w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>If like the 76.65% per of people you also use windows then you must have encountered an error like this while trying to rename your file/folder to be more precise by adding punctuations</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 698px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blogs/static/4a298277a22034e93f077a2db11334a7/487bb/warning.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 58.285714285714285%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Windows not allowing to add certain character\"\n        title=\"Windows not allowing to add certain character\"\n        src=\"/blogs/static/4a298277a22034e93f077a2db11334a7/487bb/warning.png\"\n        srcset=\"/blogs/static/4a298277a22034e93f077a2db11334a7/4edbd/warning.png 175w,\n/blogs/static/4a298277a22034e93f077a2db11334a7/13ae7/warning.png 350w,\n/blogs/static/4a298277a22034e93f077a2db11334a7/487bb/warning.png 698w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 698px) 100vw, 698px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Some of us tend to ignore the error and use some other character and it works…unless the other character also can’t be used, now it has become frustrating. Let’s get to the bottom of why windows does not allows us “Free Humans” to choose whichever name we want for our folders. After all, it’s not like I am trying to put anything special. : and ? are very common characters in use. Why can’t I name my file <code class=\"language-text\">Why did I do this?</code> and my folder <code class=\"language-text\">Childhood Images: Don&#39;t open</code> or my Marvel movies folder <code class=\"language-text\">Marvel &gt; DC</code> 😤</p>\n<h2>Let’s find out</h2>\n<p>Well, most of these restrictions are due to how windows file manager handles filename including other features around them. Hence, these characters are reserved for special purposes, actions, or denote a certain meaning. For example </p>\n<h3>Let’s use a backward slash<code class=\"language-text\">\\</code></h3>\n<p>Can’t. They are used to access contents inside a certain folder, so windows might confuse my folder <code class=\"language-text\">to\\you</code> as a folder <code class=\"language-text\">you</code> inside a folder <code class=\"language-text\">to</code> which is obviously wrong.\n<span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 700px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blogs/static/f96ae07744f18abc8d07e358fa187013/adc48/dir_name.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 27.999999999999996%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"\\ used to location\"\n        title=\"\\ used to location\"\n        src=\"/blogs/static/f96ae07744f18abc8d07e358fa187013/8c557/dir_name.png\"\n        srcset=\"/blogs/static/f96ae07744f18abc8d07e358fa187013/4edbd/dir_name.png 175w,\n/blogs/static/f96ae07744f18abc8d07e358fa187013/13ae7/dir_name.png 350w,\n/blogs/static/f96ae07744f18abc8d07e358fa187013/8c557/dir_name.png 700w,\n/blogs/static/f96ae07744f18abc8d07e358fa187013/adc48/dir_name.png 979w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<h3>Can I use a colon <code class=\"language-text\">:</code> then?</h3>\n<p>You wish. They are used to denote a drive letter which is usually at the beginning of a file path to tell windows which drive to look into for specific content. Hence having the ability to name a folder <code class=\"language-text\">E:</code> can cause problems though technically solving this challenge isn’t hard but maybe windows skipped this to avoid confusion in the mind of users who aren’t very technical but still depend on a computer for critical tasks.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 700px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blogs/static/966f4df117cf903275316897034eb996/d07b4/drives.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 39.42857142857142%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Drive letters\"\n        title=\"Drive letters\"\n        src=\"/blogs/static/966f4df117cf903275316897034eb996/29d31/drives.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/blogs/static/966f4df117cf903275316897034eb996/e52aa/drives.jpg 175w,\n/blogs/static/966f4df117cf903275316897034eb996/70ebb/drives.jpg 350w,\n/blogs/static/966f4df117cf903275316897034eb996/29d31/drives.jpg 700w,\n/blogs/static/966f4df117cf903275316897034eb996/d07b4/drives.jpg 1017w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<h3>If not backward slash <code class=\"language-text\">\\</code> then maybe forward slash <code class=\"language-text\">/</code> can be used?</h3>\n<p>Naah, Windows allows users to have shortcuts that can point to a website that might have a forward slash <code class=\"language-text\">/</code>. For example:  <code class=\"language-text\">https://twitter.com/jai_dewani</code>. </p>\n<h3>Okay so maybe a question mark <code class=\"language-text\">?</code> or an asterisk<code class=\"language-text\">*</code></h3>\n<p>Nope. If allowed it can cause problems because <code class=\"language-text\">?</code> can be used as a wildcard while searching in file explorer. Consider this example where I am searching for all folders that have <code class=\"language-text\">power</code> in their name </p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 700px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blogs/static/16f21924a372e6c634c2ea0208c9dd21/7c866/search.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 64.57142857142857%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"wildcard search in windows explorer\"\n        title=\"wildcard search in windows explorer\"\n        src=\"/blogs/static/16f21924a372e6c634c2ea0208c9dd21/29d31/search.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/blogs/static/16f21924a372e6c634c2ea0208c9dd21/e52aa/search.jpg 175w,\n/blogs/static/16f21924a372e6c634c2ea0208c9dd21/70ebb/search.jpg 350w,\n/blogs/static/16f21924a372e6c634c2ea0208c9dd21/29d31/search.jpg 700w,\n/blogs/static/16f21924a372e6c634c2ea0208c9dd21/9ecec/search.jpg 1050w,\n/blogs/static/16f21924a372e6c634c2ea0208c9dd21/7c866/search.jpg 1192w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>The same goes with <code class=\"language-text\">*</code>.\n<span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 700px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/blogs/static/3eeda759ae80857e1b6cdc50f5775644/7c866/star.jpg\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 64.57142857142857%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/jpeg;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Use of asterisk for specific file types\"\n        title=\"Use of asterisk for specific file types\"\n        src=\"/blogs/static/3eeda759ae80857e1b6cdc50f5775644/29d31/star.jpg\"\n        srcset=\"/blogs/static/3eeda759ae80857e1b6cdc50f5775644/e52aa/star.jpg 175w,\n/blogs/static/3eeda759ae80857e1b6cdc50f5775644/70ebb/star.jpg 350w,\n/blogs/static/3eeda759ae80857e1b6cdc50f5775644/29d31/star.jpg 700w,\n/blogs/static/3eeda759ae80857e1b6cdc50f5775644/9ecec/star.jpg 1050w,\n/blogs/static/3eeda759ae80857e1b6cdc50f5775644/7c866/star.jpg 1192w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<h3>I love “using” quotes</h3>\n<p>Sorry for your loss, but quotes are used to refer to file paths that have space in them for example a game inside your Program files will be referred to as <code class=\"language-text\">&quot;C:\\Program Files\\Epic Games\\rocketleague&quot;</code> due to folders having space in between them. If quotes aren’t used the system can be get confused if the statement is a 3 part command or a single complete path, if there is no space then double quotes aren’t needed.<br>\nI can’t say this for sure but windows wanted to keep the system deterministic in a way that the system shouldn’t have to make guesses as to what the user wants it to do, knocking out the possibility to guess if this input is a path to a specific file or a wildcard search.</p>\n<h3>What about less-than <code class=\"language-text\">&lt;</code> and Greater than <code class=\"language-text\">&gt;</code></h3>\n<p>Well they are also used to redirect output to some other file like the command below can redirect the output of <code class=\"language-text\">cat a.py</code> to the file <code class=\"language-text\">b.py</code> </p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"text\"><pre class=\"language-text\"><code class=\"language-text\">cat a.py &gt; b.py</code></pre></div>\n<p>or the same can be run without space in-between</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"text\"><pre class=\"language-text\"><code class=\"language-text\">cat a.py&gt;b.py  </code></pre></div>\n<p>and having > in files names can cause confusion for windows as to if the user means to redirect the output or this character part of the file name?     </p>\n<h3>And a lot more</h3>\n<p>for which I couldn’t find proper reasons to justify why they aren’t allowed to be used, maybe <a href=\"https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?text=%40jai_dewaani\">tweet</a> at me if you know any ones I missed that can be included. </p>\n<h2>But isn’t Windows smart enough?</h2>\n<p>I mean Linux and Mac OS allow users to use special characters in file/folder names that might have some other meaning or command attached to them, so why can’t windows do the same? In the end, it comes down to Windows creating a secure environment for their users because having file names as <code class=\"language-text\">*</code>, <code class=\"language-text\">-rf</code> or <code class=\"language-text\">~</code> can cause huge accidents deliberately or my mistake from the user. </p>\n<p><em>Fun Fact:</em> Most of these characters were assigned their special meaning back from MS-DOS and are continued to be supported to date in windows. </p>\n<h3>References</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://gs.statcounter.com/os-market-share/desktop/worldwide\">https://gs.statcounter.com/os-market-share/desktop/worldwide</a>  </li>\n<li><a href=\"https://www.quora.com/Why-are-special-characters-not-allowed-in-file-names\">https://www.quora.com/Why-are-special-characters-not-allowed-in-file-names</a></li>\n</ul>","frontmatter":{"title":"Windows file explorer being overprotective","date":"January 07, 2021","description":"Almost every windows user must have got an error while adding certain punctuations in a file or folder name. Why is windows exp "}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/windows-file-structure/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/carl-zeiss-interview-experience/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Carl Zeiss Interview Experience - FullStack Developer"}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/extract-wifi-passwords/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"How to extract WiFi Passwords stored on a system using Python"}}}}}